claim.claim-text:
1. A computer-implemented method comprising a plurality of steps each being performed by one or more servers executing software via one or more computer processors and in communication with one or more databases, wherein the steps comprise:
receiving, by at least one of the one or more computer processors, a seller identifier for a seller to whom a debt is owed by a consumer;
determining, by at least one of the one or more computer processors and using the seller identifier, whether the seller accepts payments upon an account issued to the consumer by an issuer;
in response to determining that the seller does not accept payments upon the account, addressing, by at least one of the one or more computer processors, a first notice to the consumer seeking collaboration from the consumer to ask the seller to accept payments upon the account; and
in response to determining that the seller does accept payments upon the account, addressing, by at least one of the one or more computer processors, a second notice to the consumer requesting the consumer to have the issuer issue to the consumer, within the account, a sub-account that is unique to the seller for making a future transaction between the consumer and the seller payable upon the sub-account.

3. The computer-implemented method as defined in claim 2, wherein:
the first notice includes at least one of:
the name of the seller;
a description that the seller does not currently accept payments on the account;
a request that the consumer approve solicitation of the seller to accept payments upon the account; and
a request for information on how to solicit the seller to accept payments upon the account; and

the confirmation includes at least one of:
the name of the consumer;
the name of the issuer that issued the sub-account,
a sub-account number;
the name of the seller; and
a credit limit of the sub-account.

7. The computer-implemented method as defined in claim 1, wherein the steps further comprise facilitating payment of the debt of the consumer owed to the seller by conducting at least one of the following:
requesting the issuer to disburse the funds from the consumer to the seller determined to accept payments upon the account for the future transaction that is payable upon the sub-account for a value matching an amount owed in the debt of the consumer to the seller determined to accept payments upon the account;
requesting the issuer to disburse the funds from the consumer to the seller determined to accept payments upon the account for the future transaction that is payable upon the account for the value matching the amount owed;
requesting a first financial institution to submit a check from the consumer to the seller for the value matching the amount owed;
requesting a second financial institution to submit a money order from the consumer to the seller for the value matching the amount owed; and
requesting a third financial institution to submit an Automated Clearing House credit transfer from the consumer to the seller for the value matching the amount owed.

8. A computer-implemented method comprising a plurality of steps each being performed by one or more servers executing software via one or more computer processors and in communication with one or more databases, wherein the steps include:
receiving, by at least one of the one or more computer processors, data about a plurality of debts owed by a consumer to a merchant;
addressing, by at least one of the one or more computer processors, a first notice to the consumer requesting the consumer to have an issuer issue to the consumer, within an account issued to the consumer by the issuer, a sub-account that is unique to the merchant for making a future transaction between the merchant and the consumer payable upon the sub-account;
aggregating, by at least one of the one or more computer processors and using the seller identifier, the debts owed to the merchant; and
addressing, by at least one of the one or more computer processors, a transmission to the issuer requesting the issuer to set a credit limit for the sub-account corresponding to the aggregated debts owed to the merchant.

14. A computer-implemented method comprising a plurality of steps each being performed by one or more servers executing software via one or more computer processors and in communication with one or more databases, wherein the steps include:
receiving, by at least one of the one or more computer processors, a buyer identifier for a buyer that owes a debt to a merchant;
determining, by at least one of the one or more computer processors and using the buyer identifier, whether the buyer accepts payments upon an account issued to the buyer by an issuer;
in response to determining that the buyer does not accept payments upon the account, addressing, by at least one of the one or more computer processors, a first notice to the merchant seeking permission from the merchant to ask the buyer to accept payments upon the account; and
in response to determining that the buyer does accept payments upon the account, addressing, by at least one of the one or more computer processors, a second notice to the buyer requesting the buyer to have the issuer issue to the buyer, within the account, a sub-account that is unique to the merchant for making a future transaction between the buyer and the merchant payable upon the sub-account.

17. The computer-implemented method as defined in claim 14, wherein the steps further comprise facilitating payment of the debt of the buyer owed to the merchant by conducting at least one of the following:
requesting the issuer to disburse the funds from the buyer determined to accept payments upon the account to the merchant for the future transaction that is payable upon the corresponding sub-account for a value matching an amount owed in the debt of the buyer owed to the merchant;
requesting the issuer to disburse the funds from the buyer determined to accept payments upon the account to the merchant for the future transaction that is payable upon the account for the value matching the amount owed;
requesting a first financial institution to submit a check from the buyer to the merchant for the value matching the amount owed;
requesting a second financial institution to submit a money order from the buyer to the merchant for the value matching the amount owed;
requesting a third financial institution to submit an Automated Clearing House credit transfer from the buyer to the merchant for the value matching the amount owed; and
requesting a fourth financial institution to submit a financial message within a cooperative of financial institutions requesting a currency transfer from the buyer to the merchant for the value matching the amount owed.

19. A computer-implemented method comprising a plurality of steps each being performed by one or more servers executing software via one or more computer processors and in communication with one or more databases, wherein the steps include:
receiving, by at least one of the one or more computer processors, data about a plurality of debts owed to a merchant by a plurality of consumers, wherein each of said plurality of debts includes a consumer identifier unique to each of said plurality of consumers;
addressing, by at least one of the one or more computer processors and to each of said plurality of consumers, a first notice requesting that the consumer have an issuer issue, within an account issued to the consumer by the issuer, a sub-account that is unique to the merchant for making a future transaction between the consumer and the merchant payable upon the sub-account; and
for each sub-account corresponding to each consumer:
aggregating, by at least one of the one or more computer processors and using the consumer identifier, the debts corresponding to the consumer; and
addressing, by at least one of the one or more computer processors, a transmission to the issuer requesting the issuer to set a credit limit for the sub-account corresponding to the aggregated debts of the consumer.
